Use the templates below to review the texture and fitting of your typeface. These test texts comprise all the two-letter combinations of Standard Modern Greek that I have been able to verify, using common words as much as possible. They are very useful for testing the typographic texture and colour, the spacing, and identifying kerning. Because there is no punctuation, and short words like articles, the texture is slightly denser than in informal real text. The vowel combinations are nearly two fifths of the combinations, so affect the texture overwhelmingly. And the alpha is the msot common letter, so small changes in the lowe-case alpha can make a big difference. 
Blocks are arranged by vowels first (α ε η ι υ ο ω), then consonants (β γ δ ζ θ κ λ μ ν ξ π ρ σ τ φ χ ψ ς). Each paragraph corresponds to the combinations of one letter. Each paragraph contains two "sentences": the first one contains words with the key letter first in the occurring pair (so the alpha-pairs go αα αβ αγ and so on).
The second "sentence" contains words with the key letter as the second in the pair (so the alpha-pairs go αα βα γα and so on).
Words in brackets represent rare combinations (usually these are names). The full stops indicate the end of each key letter sub-set.
If a combination is not present here, you do not need to take it into account when fitting the typeface. This may not matter hugely for consonant combinations, but polytonic vowels can increase the kerning pairs hugely, so it may be useful to know that, for example, vowels with dieresis never follow a consonant. 

